metadata.name: Millefoglie #101
metadata.description:
"A mille-feuille (French pronunciation: ​[mil fœj], "thousand-sheets"), also known by the names Napoleon, vanilla slice, and custard slice, is a dessert made of puff pastry layered with pastry cream. Its modern form was influenced by improvements made by Marie-Antoine Carême.

Traditionally, a mille-feuille is made up of three layers of puff pastry (pâte feuilletée), alternating with two layers of pastry cream (crème pâtissière). The top pastry layer is finished in various ways: sometimes it is topped with whipped cream, or it may be dusted with icing sugar, cocoa, pastry crumbs, or sliced almonds. It may also be glazed with icing or fondant alone, or in alternating white (icing) and brown (chocolate) or other colored icing stripes, and combed to create a marbled effect." — Wikipedia

Prints available upon request: prints@stefancontiero.com
Best enjoyed on browsers supporting Display-P3 color gamut.

metadata.name: Shapes on a Plane #121
metadata.description:
“Shapes on a Plane” explores imaginary structures and worlds through simple shapes. It’s intended for small-scale print.

As a kid I was obsessed with Lego, Duplo, wooden building blocks... anything I could make something with.

I’d spend hours building things, imagining new worlds, new machines, new concepts, then i’d take them apart and create a whole new idea to explore.

To me, this piece to me is a reminder of that time - many days spent exploring ideas with those simple objects - no care for viability, for marketability, for audiences or business. Just pure fun.

Without this time in my life, I doubt I’d have found my passion for creating in the way I do today.

metadata.name: a necessary reaction #25
metadata.description:
This piece has an interesting (to me) history. I originally started by trying to clone my IRL physical painting style in Midjourney. I got very close, then I had the idea to make a generative piece that could recreate the Midjourney recreation of my physical paintings. 

As is the nature of things, this result has departed quite a bit from my original intentions. You can scroll through the last two weeks of my Twitter feed to follow the entire process and see the original source. During the course of this writing process, crypto crashed, and the piece got darker and darker. 

There are certain combinations which will result on a matte black on matte black image (that I've taken to calling "carbon mode." A mint is in carbon mode when both palettes are 1, with a gesture on top. This is definitely the darkest mint I've done for FxHash, or even in general, and matches my mood as I watch my net worth drill to the core of the Earth. I am, however, an optimist, and I fully expect to look back on this month and laugh. Hopefully in the not-too-distant future.

metadata.name: Before/After #148
metadata.description:
A visual representation of a non-linear transformation. Each line connects a data point before the transformation has been applied to its corresponding point after the transformation has been applied. Switch to debug mode to see the untransformed and transformed points. Outline mode shows only the lines and can be used for plotting. (Plotting will likely work best on outputs where the total number of lines is low.)

The generative code is written in plain JavaScript, with the compute-intensive transformation (t-SNE) implemented in AssemblyScript and compiled to WebAssembly (WASM) for maximum performance. The final artwork is a static SVG file that can be downloaded and displayed at any resolution. No external libraries have been used.

More information about this collection is provided here: https://clauswilke.com/art/project/before-after

I would like to thank Bartholomew Littlesilver for helpful artistic feedback, Liam Egan for help with creating plottable SVGs, and BRUTALISTI and neophob for encouraging me to pursue AssemblyScript for implementing performance-critical code.

Press 'm' to cycle between normal, debug, and outline mode.

Press 's' to save as svg.

Press 'p' to save as png.

Author:
Claus O. Wilke
https://clauswilke.com/art
https://twitter.com/clauswilke

metadata.name: Chaosplot #11
metadata.description:
Continued exploration of the algorithm from "Chaospill" with a symmetric two tone style that is plotter friendly. The result can be rotated to whatever orientation works best for your display purposes. The code is presented unminified with comments and will be open sourced soon.

Live Mode Controls

Click to regenerate with a different starting seed.
1 - Save a SVG, the result is sized for 11"x17" prints with each color on a separate layer
2 - Save a PNG of the output
3 - Switch paper size to 8.5"x11" letter or A1 for different size plots
4 - Toggle HD mode which increases resolution and disables noise for printing

Code and Outputs are Copyright (C) 2022 Frank Force - Artwork is released under CC BY-NC 4.0.

metadata.name: Confini #85
metadata.description:
This is my last fxhash piece for a while, so that I can focus on my personal life. I tried to make a piece that creates the appearance of shapes scratched into the canvas. There are three carefully selected color palettes. One of them is heavily inspired by "Self-Portrait with Bandaged Ear and Pipe", by Van Gogh. These are heavily contrasting colors that I tried to get to work in coherence. One of the color palettes exists out of flavorful colors and means to spark joy in the viewer (depending on the outcome). The final color palette is one that is meant to evoke nothing but calmness. The colors are meant to remind of nature and serenity. I hope you enjoy my work.

Made in p5.js

By twistie

metadata.name: Bored Computer Screen #598
metadata.description:
"Bored Computer Screen" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022


Bored Computer Screen (BCS) is a direct descendant of Specter👻pixel⬛latte☕, where the central idea is agent and displacement. In BCS, there are agents—the small moving circles—that get their colors ripped away by the surrounding pixels. Though they occur on the same screen space, they are separated in their own cells, a simultaneous multiverse of sorts. In some iterations, a very clear voronoi pattern will appear. I didn't consciously strive for this look. It's what naturally happens, when you try to divide space, so that the borders occur exactly in between the closest neighbor. When I first saw this pattern emerge, I wanted to see how far I could get the distinct cells to influence each other. The idea that the same algorithmic processes can happen many times but still separately in a single piece has always interested me (and explored in the Infinite Browse series). BCS is an extension of that, albeit a little more chaotic.

Note:
- Best experience on browsers and devices with support for WebGL2 

Made by Sam Tsao (@sam___tsao) with P5, P5Fbo and perlinjs.
